Yes — here is a cleaned and safer buildspec.yml for your CodeBuild job. It uses version: 0.2, supports bash shell syntax, allows runtime selection with runtime-versions, and uses standard artifacts output so logs can be collected after the run.

Rewritten buildspec
This version fixes the shell condition syntax, uses python3, handles empty SOURCE_PREFIX cleanly, and passes worker values to the script.

text
version: 0.2

env:
  shell: bash
  variables:
    BUCKET: ""
    SOURCE_PREFIX: ""
    DRY_RUN: "true"
    PHASE: "all"
    RESTORE_DAYS: "7"
    RESTORE_TIER: "Standard"
    POLL_SECONDS: "300"
    BUCKET_WORKERS: "4"
    OBJECT_WORKERS: "32"
    SCRIPT_S3_URI: "s3://ops-alerting-bucket/s3_restore/restore_v2.py"

phases:
  install:
    runtime-versions:
      python: 3.11
    commands:
      - set -euo pipefail
      - echo "Installing dependencies..."
      - python3 --version
      - pip3 install --no-cache-dir boto3 requests

  pre_build:
    commands:
      - set -euo pipefail
      - echo "Downloading script from S3..."
      - aws s3 cp "${SCRIPT_S3_URI}" ./restore_v2.py
      - chmod +x ./restore_v2.py
      - mkdir -p logs
      - echo "Bucket             : ${BUCKET}"
      - echo "Source Prefix      : ${SOURCE_PREFIX}"
      - echo "Dry Run            : ${DRY_RUN}"
      - echo "Phase              : ${PHASE}"
      - echo "Restore Tier       : ${RESTORE_TIER}"
      - echo "Restore Days       : ${RESTORE_DAYS}"
      - echo "Poll Seconds       : ${POLL_SECONDS}"
      - echo "Bucket Workers     : ${BUCKET_WORKERS}"
      - echo "Object Workers     : ${OBJECT_WORKERS}"

  build:
    commands:
      - set -euo pipefail
      - |
        CMD="python3 ./restore_v2.py --bucket \"${BUCKET}\" --phase \"${PHASE}\" --tier \"${RESTORE_TIER}\" --days \"${RESTORE_DAYS}\" --poll-seconds \"${POLL_SECONDS}\" --bucket-workers \"${BUCKET_WORKERS}\" --object-workers \"${OBJECT_WORKERS}\" --output-dir logs"

        if [ -n "${SOURCE_PREFIX}" ]; then
          CMD="${CMD} --source-prefix \"${SOURCE_PREFIX}\""
        fi

        if [ "${DRY_RUN}" = "true" ] || [ "${DRY_RUN}" = "True" ]; then
          CMD="${CMD} --dry-run"
        else
          CMD="${CMD} --wait"
        fi

        echo "Executing command:"
        echo "${CMD}"
        eval "${CMD}"

  post_build:
    commands:
      - echo "Build completed on $(date)"
      - echo "Generated files:"
      - ls -R logs || true

artifacts:
  files:
    - logs/**/*
    - restore_v2.py
  discard-paths: no
What this fixes
Your screenshot showed malformed if tests, including missing spaces before ] and combined conditions inside one bracket expression, which is why the build likely failed in CodeBuild shell execution. This rewritten version uses bash explicitly and builds one command string safely based on whether SOURCE_PREFIX is empty and whether DRY_RUN is true.

Important note
If your actual Python file is the multi-bucket version, this buildspec should call the matching arguments only. The version above assumes restore_v2.py supports --bucket-workers and --object-workers; if you are still using the single-bucket script, those options will fail and should be removed.

If you want bucket-wide mode
To process the whole bucket, just leave:

